1
00:00:00,622 --> 00:00:30,561
Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma sambuddhassa Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma sambuddhassa Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma sambuddhassa Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-awakened one.

2
00:00:32,566 --> 00:00:46,625
So what I'm hoping to do for the rest of the year is go through the whole teaching really in little short talks and the place to start of course is with his declaration of the Four Noble Truths

3
00:00:46,993 --> 00:00:54,469
And if you were to choose one word upon which all his teaching is based, it would have to be the word dukkha.

4
00:00:55,189 --> 00:01:04,429
So this dukkha just means hard to bear and it's translated variously as suffering, dissatisfaction, discomfort and so forth.

5
00:01:04,679 --> 00:01:07,923
but it really covers the whole of life.

6
00:01:08,703 --> 00:01:18,234
So it begins with dukkata, which means the suffering of suffering or the dissatisfaction of dissatisfaction.

7
00:01:18,676 --> 00:01:29,347
In other words, ordinary physical pain, mental anguish, et cetera, et cetera, are just natural to the human condition.

8
00:01:29,868 --> 00:01:33,352
But what makes it suffering is the way we react.

9
00:01:33,787 --> 00:01:38,394
And it's knowing that that allows us to find the escape out of suffering.

10
00:01:39,194 --> 00:01:41,397
So that's what we're doing when we're meditating.

11
00:01:41,477 --> 00:01:49,429
Of course, when we're in posture, we note something coming up, a pain in the knee or something, and we note the reaction to it.

12
00:01:50,209 --> 00:02:03,406
And when we can stand apart from the reaction, we find ourselves in a place which is not suffering, even though the environment, the pain in the knee and the not wanting of the pain in the knee is not pleasant.

13
00:02:03,825 --> 00:02:11,633
So it's making that sort of distinction when it comes to just the pains and woes of life.

14
00:02:12,395 --> 00:02:15,507
So even taking something like

15
00:02:16,026 --> 00:02:20,110
something very heavy like a death, the death of somebody close to us.

16
00:02:20,491 --> 00:02:25,597
So a tremendous amount of grief and heart suffering.

17
00:02:26,397 --> 00:02:31,742
But then there's the reaction to that, which is sometimes a desire not to face it.

18
00:02:31,804 --> 00:02:37,489
So it remains in the system as a turbulence, and sometimes the desire to indulge it.

19
00:02:37,528 --> 00:02:44,717
So you get into this wrong relationship with grief, where if you stop grieving, you think you've stopped loving.

20
00:02:44,697 --> 00:03:08,865
so but when we sort of feel it as a feeling in in ourselves we're standing apart from it and that separation from the reaction that we've had is the nibonic gap and that's what we have to really keep rediscovering for ourselves and of course in these situations the heart heals itself

21
00:03:10,177 --> 00:03:17,945
Now on the obverse side of that, of course, is everything to do with pleasure, excuse me, the pleasures and joys of life.

22
00:03:17,966 --> 00:03:22,290
So here we have a different problem to do with indulgence.

23
00:03:22,311 --> 00:03:30,159
Now what indulgence simply means is that we're using something, we're becoming dependent on something in order to be happy.

24
00:03:30,961 --> 00:03:39,729
Everybody has their own definition of what makes them happy and everybody has their own particular feeling as to what happiness is.

25
00:03:39,710 --> 00:03:44,622
And we tend to believe that that's the purpose of our lives, to feel happy.

26
00:03:46,072 --> 00:03:55,941
When Saira Upandita turned up at IMS once, a woman said to him, you know, I'm so happy to see you.

27
00:03:56,641 --> 00:04:00,746
And he replied in Burmese, but the translator didn't translate it.

28
00:04:01,606 --> 00:04:05,469
Afterwards, she went to the translator and asked, what did he say?

29
00:04:05,509 --> 00:04:08,193
He said, I haven't come here to make you happy.

30
00:04:08,353 --> 00:04:09,753
I've come here to make you aware.

31
00:04:10,574 --> 00:04:14,778
And that's the crucial point about the Buddha's teachings.

32
00:04:15,603 --> 00:04:25,661
And of course, when we do indulge, there is always consequences, you know, the grief of loss, the anxiety of loss, you know, paying out loads for insurance.

33
00:04:26,642 --> 00:04:32,514
And there's the anger, you know, not getting what you want, the frustration of not getting what you want.

34
00:04:32,533 --> 00:04:38,826
And then, of course, the boredom, what used to make you happy and joyful, now you find boring.

35
00:04:38,805 --> 00:04:47,648
So there's a whole load of mental dis-eases that comes through the process of attachment, through the process of indulgence.

36
00:04:47,668 --> 00:04:51,999
And this is all contained in that little phrase, dukkha, dukkhata.

37
00:04:52,019 --> 00:04:53,423
It's one type of suffering.

38
00:04:55,023 --> 00:04:57,826
Now the second type is to do with impermanence.

39
00:04:58,747 --> 00:05:06,795
And this is basically not really coming to terms with the fact that everything arises and passes away.

40
00:05:07,437 --> 00:05:11,242
Not only does everything arise and pass away, nothing ever repeats.

41
00:05:12,041 --> 00:05:19,870
So there's actually nothing in this universe, in our universe, in our lives that we can rely upon, right?

42
00:05:19,891 --> 00:05:23,055
Anything can disappear at any moment.

43
00:05:23,035 --> 00:05:28,894
So it's coming to terms with that, which is really understanding this process of change.

44
00:05:30,324 --> 00:05:36,771
Now we're especially, should we say, fortunate in Britain because of our weather.

45
00:05:37,153 --> 00:05:56,434
The weather is constantly changing and therefore we can never make absolute plans as to when you want to go for a walk because I'm a fair weather walker and you make a plan to walk on such a day and of course it rains or it rains and snows or it does everything else apart from sunshine.

46
00:05:56,413 --> 00:06:09,589
So this whole idea of impermanence comes across when we actually look at what we arrange sometimes and sometimes we can't make it.

47
00:06:10,531 --> 00:06:19,560
And of course, at a deeper level, this whole impermanence, of course, is taking us to the whole process of aging and final death.

48
00:06:20,182 --> 00:06:23,586
And that's the difficult one to come to terms with, of course.

49
00:06:24,899 --> 00:06:42,367
but it's this it's the it's the quiet gentle remembrance at all times you know just just just there that everything comes to an end life comes to an end now you might think by reminding myself of that i'm going to make myself depressed but

50
00:06:42,348 --> 00:06:56,862
but what happens is of course you find yourself living more in the moment living more in the moment you come to appreciate the moment more and therefore paradoxically your life becomes much more joyful for it

51
00:06:57,451 --> 00:07:14,870
In the medieval times, of course, it was very regular to have your, what was it called, momentum, mori momentum, your reminder of death, a little skull on your death or somewhere, so that you never actually forgot that life is short.

52
00:07:16,012 --> 00:07:26,242
And that whole attitude of coming to terms with impermanence is part and parcel of our practice.

53
00:07:26,898 --> 00:07:30,182
The final one is to do with the concept of self.

54
00:07:30,644 --> 00:07:41,841
The concept of self creates a substantiality, something that is real, whole, entire unto itself.

55
00:07:42,302 --> 00:07:46,189
But actually, when we look even

56
00:07:46,793 --> 00:08:05,680
even a little bit deeper we can see that everything is compounded everything is made up of little bits and pieces and these little bits and pieces are dependent on other little bits and pieces and so this whole planet as we know is a living organism with little bits and pieces

57
00:08:05,660 --> 00:08:32,780
dependent on some other little bits and pieces and it's beginning to dissolve beginning to deconstruct our experience of ourselves which is part and parcel of that process now we wouldn't do that or we'd be afraid to do that if when we just when we when we actually deconstruct everything we find there's nothing there I mean that would be terrible

58
00:08:33,097 --> 00:08:41,488
But what the Buddha is saying is that hidden within this organism, there is something which doesn't die.

59
00:08:41,528 --> 00:08:43,730
It wasn't born, doesn't die.

60
00:08:44,251 --> 00:08:45,874
It's not even conditioned.

61
00:08:46,634 --> 00:08:47,416
Now, where is it?

62
00:08:47,475 --> 00:08:49,038
What could it possibly be?

63
00:08:49,097 --> 00:08:53,503
And that's the process again of our meditation.

64
00:08:54,799 --> 00:09:06,067
So this sense of self is, shall we say, the fundamental delusion that lies at the basis of all our unhappinesses.

65
00:09:06,807 --> 00:09:10,918
It's the point where the awareness within us

66
00:09:11,017 --> 00:09:36,567
begins to experience this organism as itself that's the big point of contact and it's right there that the the whole trouble of delusion begins and the dependent origination begins with that phrase avidya you know delusion not knowing it's not a culpable thing it's just the way it is now

67
00:09:37,190 --> 00:09:38,312
How do we know?

68
00:09:38,352 --> 00:09:42,645
How do we know when any of these delusions are arising?

69
00:09:42,706 --> 00:09:52,312
How do we know, you know, sorry, once we've sussed this out, once we've understood this, how do we know when it's activated?

70
00:09:52,293 --> 00:09:53,195
This is the point.

71
00:09:53,215 --> 00:09:59,751
How do we know when we are under the spell of these misunderstandings?

72
00:09:59,772 --> 00:10:04,583
So this is where the genius, you might say, or the real insight of the Buddha lies.

73
00:10:04,924 --> 00:10:08,293
It lies right there in our desires.

74
00:10:08,594 --> 00:10:15,630
So if we're aware of a desire, we'll be able to pinpoint what is causing that desire.

75
00:10:16,452 --> 00:10:19,480
And if it's wholesome, of course we empower it.

76
00:10:19,821 --> 00:10:25,354
But if it's not wholesome, then we have to sit with that energy until it dies away.

77
00:10:25,333 --> 00:10:40,461
And to be aware of a desire as it rises takes that bit of apamado, it's his favourite word, one of his favourite words, which of course, it's his second to last word in life.

78
00:10:41,001 --> 00:10:44,928
Apamado, that's right.

79
00:10:44,908 --> 00:10:47,474
Strive diligently for your liberation.

80
00:10:47,913 --> 00:10:56,349
So it's that sense of constantly bringing ourselves back to the present moment and being awake to any little desire that comes up.

81
00:10:57,049 --> 00:10:59,975
Most desires, you know, are neither here nor there.

82
00:11:00,456 --> 00:11:04,182
There's a desire in me to wave my hand about like I'm doing now.

83
00:11:05,091 --> 00:11:07,533
It's not something I'm going to be too bothered about.

84
00:11:08,235 --> 00:11:23,307
But if a desire is for something which I immediately perceive as unwholesome, unskillful, unvirtuous, then if I'm right there with the initial movement of that desire, the choice arises.

85
00:11:24,107 --> 00:11:25,889
Once I've activated it, that's it.

86
00:11:25,950 --> 00:11:29,312
I've lost that moment of little bit of choice.

87
00:11:29,932 --> 00:11:34,136
And once it's activated, then of course there are going to be results.

88
00:11:35,347 --> 00:11:45,173
So that second noble truth, the noble truth that desire is the cause of suffering, that's how the delusions manifest.

89
00:11:46,235 --> 00:11:50,285
And then of course he says that there is an end to this suffering.

90
00:11:50,467 --> 00:11:55,994
And then finally, there's the path that he delineates, which is a bit too much for us to go into this evening.

91
00:11:56,474 --> 00:12:00,557
But most of you know it, it begins with right understanding, which is what we're doing now.

92
00:12:00,618 --> 00:12:04,062
And that of course changes our attitudes.

93
00:12:04,522 --> 00:12:10,748
And when our attitudes change, it affects the way we speak and what we do and our livelihood.

94
00:12:11,269 --> 00:12:16,193
So it all reverts back to this really understanding the way things are.

95
00:12:16,734 --> 00:12:19,496
And then through that process of

96
00:12:19,476 --> 00:12:35,022
Not activating those desires that are unwholesome and activating those desires that are wholesome that the attitude changes and very slowly we pull ourselves out of the morass of human suffering.

97
00:12:36,638 --> 00:12:41,904
But let's go back to the third one, you see, which is, of course, there is an end to suffering.

98
00:12:42,384 --> 00:12:44,727
And the word he gives for that is Nibbāna.

99
00:12:45,168 --> 00:12:47,230
And it's translated in various ways.

100
00:12:47,851 --> 00:12:52,357
Some of it is, shall we say, creative etymology.

101
00:12:53,519 --> 00:13:01,870
But the two main ones are no desire and unshackled, unshackled, you see, unfettered.

102
00:13:01,850 --> 00:13:07,380
Now, some of you will know the ten fetters that keep us at this level of existence.

103
00:13:07,400 --> 00:13:13,232
And it's unfettering those that releases this awareness, which is the Buddha within.

104
00:13:13,293 --> 00:13:22,812
And so I'd like to end my little homily with a quote from Meiji Kyao.

105
00:13:25,542 --> 00:13:33,375
Mechi Keau was a Thai nun who died in 1991, so she's absolutely contemporary.

106
00:13:33,914 --> 00:13:37,041
She was a student of Ajahn Mahabua.

107
00:13:37,061 --> 00:13:41,086
Some of you might know his writings.

108
00:13:41,067 --> 00:13:56,546
and she worked with her, she worked with him and then once she became liberated she went back to look after her nuns and that's what she did really for the rest of her life.

109
00:13:57,125 --> 00:14:04,375
Died when she was about 91 if I remember of lung cancer.

110
00:14:06,346 --> 00:14:13,836
So now this is what she says, which tells us how somebody who's fully liberated actually experiences life.

111
00:14:14,996 --> 00:14:16,860
So remember, she's fully engaged.

112
00:14:17,080 --> 00:14:23,808
She's there with the nuns and lay people who come, but mainly her concern seems to have been to guide her nuns.

113
00:14:24,509 --> 00:14:26,972
So she's fully engaged in life, right?

114
00:14:27,573 --> 00:14:34,243
And this is what she says, which tells us how that engagement is, how it manifests.

115
00:14:35,017 --> 00:14:42,052
This is what she says, body, mind and essence are all distinct and separate realities.

116
00:14:42,373 --> 00:14:52,975
So there's three parts to us, the body, our physicality, our mentality and this, what she here calls essence, right, that which is.

117
00:14:55,283 --> 00:15:19,451
absolutely everything is known right which means that whatever comes into the awareness whatever whatever arises on the screen of consciousness she knows it you know her mind isn't somewhere else earth water fire and wind so these remember are your five uh your four your four great elements i won't go into detail i'm presuming you know this

118
00:15:20,038 --> 00:15:33,297
Then there's feeling, sorry, the body, feeling, perceptions, conceptual thinking, and then there are the habits that we have, and finally consciousness.

119
00:15:34,317 --> 00:15:39,264
She knows when sounds, sights, smells, tastes, touches and emotions arise.

120
00:15:39,806 --> 00:15:44,672
She knows when, now this is interesting, when greed, anger and delusion arise.

121
00:15:45,113 --> 00:15:48,898
All are known, I know them as they exist,

122
00:15:49,519 --> 00:16:19,289
in their natural states now it might surprise you to think that somebody who's fully liberated still has negative unwholesome thoughts arise but remember the mind is now sort of habituated in a way of thinking but the distinction between somebody who's an arahat and us is that they are traces in the mind that have no pull they have no attraction and therefore they just arise and pass away

123
00:16:19,269 --> 00:16:23,804
Whereas our habit, of course, is to jump and grab hold of them and off we go.

124
00:16:23,825 --> 00:16:29,263
And what she's saying is that these are just traces that pass through the mind.

125
00:16:30,491 --> 00:16:52,533
now no matter how much i'm exposed to them i'm unable to detect even an instant when they have any power over my heart and that's her next word for this buddha within her heart right it doesn't remember it's not it's not the emotional heart this isn't emotion this is her real being

126
00:16:52,514 --> 00:16:54,136
And they have no power over it.

127
00:16:54,258 --> 00:16:55,519
The awareness is there.

128
00:16:56,702 --> 00:16:59,908
Now we experience that in our meditation on occasion.

129
00:17:00,289 --> 00:17:05,981
On occasion when we're observing things rising, passing away, we're in this state.

130
00:17:06,061 --> 00:17:08,446
We're having a little touch of nibbana.

131
00:17:10,064 --> 00:17:32,510
all these things arise and cease they're forever changing but the presence that's the third word she uses to describe this awareness this buddha nature but the presence that knows them never changes for an instant it is forever unborn and undying this is the end of suffering

132
00:17:32,913 --> 00:17:39,101
So I've never come across a more clear statement as to how an Arahant experiences life.

133
00:17:39,642 --> 00:17:44,087
Not even the Buddha, which may be surprising.

134
00:17:44,749 --> 00:17:59,950
The Buddha has many statements about Nibbāna and about that state of mind, but I've never seen it expressed, as it were, in a way that the ordinary meditator can grasp.

135
00:17:59,930 --> 00:18:07,637
So there she is, looking after her nuns, always in the moment, aware of what's actually happening.

136
00:18:08,358 --> 00:18:14,785
And whenever something slightly negative arises in the mind, it simply arises and passes away.

137
00:18:14,826 --> 00:18:19,089
It doesn't enter into her heart, into her awareness.

138
00:18:20,310 --> 00:18:23,835
So I'm hoping that you find that inspiring.

139
00:18:23,994 --> 00:18:26,798
I personally find it very inspiring.

140
00:18:27,840 --> 00:18:42,998
And I can only hope my words have been of some assistance, that I have not caused confusion, and that by your total devotion to the practice, you will be liberated from all suffering sooner rather than later.

